Here is the `ProofJSON` representation of the provided theorems and proofs:

```
[
  {
    "type": "theorem",
    "name": "Theorem 1",
    "statement": "Suppose f: R -> R is a continuous function such that f''(x) > 0 for all x in R. Then f(x) is unbounded as x -> infinity.",
    "status": "proved",
    "proof": [
      {
        "type": "observation",
        "statement": "If f''(x) > 0 for all x in R, then f is strictly convex."
      },
      {
        "type": "assumption",
        "statement": "Suppose f(x) approaches a finite limit L as x -> infinity."
      },
      {
        "type": "assertion",
        "claim": "For some sufficiently large x, f(x) is arbitrarily close to L.",
        "deduced-from": ["The assumption that f(x) approaches a finite limit L as x -> infinity"]
      },
      {
        "type": "assertion",
        "claim": "Due to the strict convexity of f, for any x' > x, f(x') > f(x).",
        "deduced-from": ["The observation that f is strictly convex if f''(x) > 0"]
      },
      {
        "type": "assertion",
        "claim": "Therefore, f(x) is unbounded as x -> infinity.",
        "justification": "Contradicts the assumption that f(x) is close to L."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "theorem",
    "name": "Theorem 2",
    "statement": "Suppose f: R -> R is a continuous function such that f''(x) > 0 for all x in R. Then f(x) is unbounded as x -> -infinity.",
    "status": "proved",
    "proof": [
      {
        "type": "observation",
        "statement": "If f''(x) > 0 for all x in R, then f is strictly convex."
      },
      {
        "type": "assumption",
        "statement": "Suppose f(x) approaches a finite limit L as x -> -infinity."
      },
      {
        "type": "assertion",
        "claim": "For some sufficiently small x (i.e., a large negative number), f(x) is arbitrarily close to L.",
        "deduced-from": ["The assumption that f(x) approaches a finite limit L as x -> -infinity"]
      },
      {
        "type": "assertion",
        "claim": "Due to the strict convexity of f, for any x' < x, f(x') > f(x).",
        "deduced-from": ["The observation that f is strictly convex if f''(x) > 0"]
      },
      {
        "type": "assertion",
        "claim": "Therefore, f(x) is unbounded as x -> -infinity.",
        "justification": "Contradicts the assumption that f(x) is close to L."
      }
    ]
  }
]
```

Note that in the `ProofJSON` format, we first state the theorems, then provide their proofs. Each step in the proof is clearly delineated, and the logical flow is maintained. For each assertion, we indicate the statements or observations it is deduced from, providing a clear chain of reasoning. The final assertion in each proof provides the conclusion of the theorem.

Here is the `ProofJSON` representation of the above proofs:

```
[
    {
        "type": "theorem",
        "name": "Theorem 1",
        "statement": "If f:R -> R is a continuous function and f''(x) > 0 for all x in R, then f is strictly convex.",
        "status": "proved",
        "proof": [
            {
                "type": "assertion",
                "claim": "f is strictly convex.",
                "deduced-from": [
                    "The second derivative test for convexity",
                    "f''(x) > 0 for all x in R"
                ]
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "type": "theorem",
        "name": "Theorem 2",
        "statement": "If f is strictly convex, its derivative f' is nondecreasing.",
        "status": "proved",
        "proof": [
            {
                "type": "assertion",
                "claim": "f' is nondecreasing.",
                "deduced-from": [
                    "The characterization of convex functions",
                    "For any x<y<z, (f(y)-f(x))/(y-x) <= (f(z)-f(y))/(z-y)"
                ]
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "type": "theorem",
        "name": "Theorem 3",
        "statement": "If f''(x) > 0 for all x in R, then f is unbounded.",
        "status": "proved",
        "proof": [
            {
                "type": "assumption",
                "statement": "f is bounded."
            },
            {
                "type": "assertion",
                "claim": "f is strictly convex.",
                "deduced-from": [
                    "Theorem 1"
                ]
            },
            {
                "type": "assertion",
                "claim": "f' is nondecreasing.",
                "deduced-from": [
                    "Theorem 2"
                ]
            },
            {
                "type": "assertion",
                "claim": "f' is nondecreasing and f''(x) > 0 for all x in R contradict the assumption that f is bounded.",
                "deduced-from": [
                    {
                        "result": "The Intermediate Value Theorem",
                        "applied-to": "the values f'(a), f'(b), and the interval (f'(a),f'(b))"
                    },
                    "f''(x) > 0 for all x in R"
                ]
            },
            {
                "type": "assertion",
                "claim": "f is unbounded.",
                "deduced-from": [
                    "Contradiction from the assumption that f is bounded."
                ]
            }
        ]
    }
]
```

This `ProofJSON` representation is a list of three theorems, each of which has a proof composed of multiple assertions. In these assertions, the "deduced-from" fields specify the underlying basis for each step in the proof. For instance, in the proof of Theorem 3, the application of the Intermediate Value Theorem is specified in the "deduced-from" field for the claim that the boundedness of $f$ contradicts the nondecreasing nature of $f'$ and the positivity of $f''$.

