    "status": "proved",
    "proof": [
      {
        "type": "assumption",
        "statement": "f: ℝ → ℝ is a continuous function such that f''(x) > 0 for all x ∈ ℝ."
      },
      {
        "type": "assumption",
        "statement": "For the sake of contradiction, assume that f is bounded."
      },
      {
        "type": "assertion",
        "claim": "There exist a, b ∈ ℝ such that f(a) = inf_{x ∈ ℝ} f(x) and f(b) = sup_{x ∈ ℝ} f(x).",
        "deduced-from": [
          "f is bounded",
          "Extreme Value Theorem"
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "observation",
        "statement": "As f''(x) > 0 for all x ∈ ℝ, the function f is strictly convex."
      },
      {
        "type": "assertion",
        "claim": "A strictly convex function can only achieve its infimum and supremum at the endpoints of its interval.",
        "deduced-from": ["f is strictly convex"]
      },
      {
        "type": "observation",
        "statement": "The domain of f is ℝ, which has no endpoints."
      },
      {
        "type": "assertion",
        "claim": "This leads to a contradiction with our earlier assumption that f is bounded.",
        "deduced-from": ["f achieves its infimum and supremum at the endpoints of its interval", "The domain of f has no endpoints"]
      },
      {
        "type": "observation",
        "statement": "Hence, the function f must be unbounded."
      }
    ]
  }
]
```

In this JSON representation of the proof, each step of the reasoning is captured as an object in the `proof` array. Each object includes the type of statement (like an assumption, assertion, or observation), and the content of the statement. Assertions also include from what they were deduced. The whole proof is wrapped in a `theorem` object, which includes the statement of the theorem and its proof status as "proved".

